                <head type="CCC">Nicholas Love OCarth, The Mirrour of the blessyd Lyf of Christ. Treatise on the
                    Sacrament</head>

                <head type="James">Mirror of the Life of Christ etc.</head>

                <p function="Codicology"><material>Vellum</material>, <measureGrp type="CCC">
                        <height unit="mm">320</height>
                        <width unit="mm">220</width>
                    </measureGrp><measureGrp type="James">12.6 x 8.7</measureGrp>, <extent>ff. 142 + 1</extent>,
                        <layout>36 lines to a page</layout>. Cent. <origDate>xv</origDate>, <handNote>in a good clear
                        hand, probably a little earlier than <ref type="ms" target="CCC142">MS 142</ref></handNote>.</p>

                <p><label>Collation:</label>
                    <collation>1 flyleaf, a<num>8</num> (wants 1) b<num>8</num>-s<num>8</num> (wants 8)</collation>.</p>

                <p function="Additions">On the flyleaf: xxvi<abbr rend="superscript">s</abbr> viii<abbr
                        rend="superscript">d</abbr>.</p>





                <p type="CCC">
                    <foliation>ff. a + i + 1-142 + b</foliation>.</p>




                <msContents>

                    <textLang mainLang="enm" otherLangs="lat">Middle English and Latin.</textLang>
                    <label>Contents</label>

                    <msItem n="1" locusStart="1r" locusEnd="132v">

                        <head type="CCC"><name type="author">Nicholas Love OCarth</name>, <title>The Mirrour of the
                                blessyd Lyf of Christ</title></head>

                        <head type="James">
                            <title>Mirror of the Life of Christ</title>
                        </head>


                        <head type="Nasmith">
                            <title>The mirrour of the blessid lyf of Ihesu</title>
                        </head>


                        <ab>The first leaf with 46 capitula is gone</ab>
                        <ab locus="1r">The note <q>Adtendite lector</q> follows the capitula: but not the
                            memorandum</ab>
                        <ab locus="1v">Prohemium with <decoNote>good border and initial</decoNote> on f.
                                <locus>1v</locus></ab>
                        <ab locus="4v">Text, <decoNote>fine initial and partial border</decoNote></ab>
                        <ab>On f. <locus>128r</locus> is pasted a bit of a leaf of a <handNote>very finely
                                written</handNote> Breviary(?) with a <decoNote>beautiful piece of border</decoNote>:
                            cent. <date>xiv-xv</date></ab>


                    </msItem>


                    <msItem n="2" locusStart="132v" locusEnd="142r">

                        <head type="CCC">
                            <title>Treatise on the Sacrament</title>
                        </head>


                        <head type="Nasmith">
                            <title>Treatise of the sacrament</title>
                        </head>


                        <ab>The tract on the Sacrament begins on f. <locus>132v</locus></ab>
                        <ab>Ending</ab>
                        <explicit locus="142r">&#254;y life blessid with outen endynge. Amen</explicit>
                        <rubric locusNew="142r">Lorde Ihesu &#254;y blissed life helpe and comforte oure wrecchid
                            life</rubric>

                        <ab>
                            <quote>The name of the author or possessor of this book was formerly written in golden
                                letters on a vacant page at the end, but thro' time or accident is now partly defaced;
                                the only remaining words are these, <q><name type="person">Johannes Monke</name> ...
                                        <name type="person">Michael</name>...</q></quote>
                        </ab>
                        <ab>On f. <locus>142v</locus> at top in gold are the names<lb/>
                            <q><name type="person">Iohannes Monke</name> ... <name type="person">Michael</name></q> but
                            I see no trace of erasure. They have been meant to stand over a picture which was never
                            drawn</ab>


                    </msItem>




                </msContents>




